Descriptor: Thousands of people take to the streets of downtown Oakland to protest President Trump's inauguration on Jan. 20. By evening, a smaller group clashes with police, but only one arrest is reported.
In San Francisco, thousands gather at several events to protest President Trump's inaguration. A long chain of people tries to link hands across the Golden Gate Bridge in a peaceful demonstration.
About a dozen people handcuff themselves to Caltrain tracks in San Francisco — they have to be cut free — to protest President Trump's inauguration.
Thousands of students, faculty and members of the UC Berkeley community meet on campus for a peaceful rally against President Trump's inauguration.

Tens of thousands of people take to the streets of San Francisco on Jan. 21, the day after President Trump took office, in one of a series of Women's Marches held around the world to support women's rights.
In one of the largest Oakland protests in recent memory, tens of thousands of particpants gather for the city's Women's March, with many denouncing President Trump's inauguration.

Even in Bay Area suburbs, crowds join the Women's March protests on Jan. 21. Several hundred people, joined by several state senators, attend a rally in Walnut Creek, where protests don't typically happen.

Two days after President Trump signed an executive order paving the way for the contested Dakota Access Pipeline, hundreds of protesters gather outside San Francisco's Federal Building on Jan. 26 to project "#NODAPL" in 10-foot-high letters on the building's wall.
Hundreds of people descend on San Francisco International Airport on Jan. 28 to protest President Trump's ban on travel from seven predominantly Muslim countries.
Hundreds show up outside an Islamic center in Alameda to protest President Trump's travel ban.
On Jan. 30, hundreds of Google employees at the tech giant's Mountain View headquarters protest President Trump's executive order restricting immigration from seven predominantly Muslim countries.

Damages: $100,000 on Berkeley's campus, thousands more in Berkeley proper.
Descriptor: Thousands of protesters gather at UC Berkeley to demonstrate against a planned speech by the far-right provocateur (then with Breibart News) Milo Yiannopoulos. Masked anarchists tear down fences and smash windows at the student center, forcing the event to be canceled.
A few dozen protesters brave the rain Feb. 17 to march to San Francisco's Ferry Building and project a series of images critical of the president on the side facing the Embarcadero.

About 600 of Sen. Dianne Feinstein's constituents Feb. 26 hold an "empty chair" town hall at an Oakland school that they Periscope live in an effort to pressure Feinstein into holding a public town hall and urge her to be more proactively against the Trump administration.

On March 4, dozens of supporters of President Trump gather at Berkeley's Civic Center Park but are greatly outnumberd by counter-demonstrators. Fights break out, bricks are thrown and there are arrests for assault with a deadly weapon.
Several thousand people gathered March 8 at San Jose's City Hall for a lunchtime rally to kick off International Women's Day.
On March 8, International Women's Day, a couple of hundred protesters gather at UC Berkeley's Sproul Plaza to rally for abortion rights and other issues.
On International Women's Day — "A Day Without a Woman," as protesters called it — hundreds of women strike to denounce sexism and gender inequalities in San Francisco.
International Women's Day: Hundreds of women, joined by male supporters, march through the streets of Oakland to rail against sexism and demand gender equity.
On Pi Day, hundreds of Silicon Valley techies rally outside City Hall in Palo Alto to protest President Trump's planned revised executive order restricting immigration.

In the second pro-Trump rally in Berkeley in as many months, right-wingers, liberals and anti-fascists clash at Civic Center Park before violence spills out to the streets of Berkeley. Twenty people are arrested, including two on outstanding warrants from a violent March 4 protest.

Thousands of demonstrators in San Francisco, joined by sister marches across the country, on tax day march from Civic Center Plaza to the Embarcadero via Market Street to demand the release of President Trump's tax returns.

Dozens of attendees of Sen. Dianne Feinstein's April 17 town hall at the Scottish Rite Masonic Center on 19th Avenue  interrupt her remarks in an effort to urge the veteran lawmaker to be more forceful in her opposition to the Trump administration.

March for Science: Dressed as everything from dinosaurs to science superheroes, tens of thousands of people on Earth Day march from City Hall and the Ferry Building to promote science and protest President Trump's proposed cuts to the Environmental Protection Agency.
